{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774643281,"nonce":"pMd6cFWQIFl7+YtWOVEG4fB5RaU=","message":"Ambiguity clarification for the issue body:\n\n\"The adversarial training loop\" and \"adversarial gradient\" refer specifically to the minimax adversarial training loop (train_minimax.py) where the controller and adversary (GaussianBumpAdversary) are trained alternately. This is distinct from APT (Madry-style adversarial perturbation training) which was implemented as a pre_step_fn hook on TaskTrainer (see issue c05998e). The 14-minute compilation and 12 host-TPU round-trips are specific to the minimax loop structure with its alternating controller/adversary gradient updates.\n\nThe \"alternating controller/adversary updates\" in Known Issue #2 refers to the minimax training loop where each training step involves: (1) adversary inner optimization steps (gradient ascent on adversary parameters to maximize loss), then (2) controller outer step (gradient descent on controller parameters to minimize loss against the adversary-chosen perturbation). This structure requires multiple gradient computations per training step.\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}